Temperatures rising increasingly could lead to the total disappearance of the Arctic ice cap by 2050.
Butterflies and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is omnipresent in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases is increasing as air pollution worsens.
We do, however, have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let's see these people, more numerous day by day, ready to act to question their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
They too are taking action, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
However, it's the politicians and policymakers, at both national and European levels, who often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let's make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three key areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no choice: the EU's net carbon dioxide emissions must be brought to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can invest heavily in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energy, as well as key technologies such as hydrogen fuel cells, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private vehicles, public transport, as well as maritime and air freight.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the leading continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in the responsible use of resources and become a genuine circular economy that minimizes waste.
Each year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do a lot better, which will require us to focus on four areas: food waste and the bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work today, for instance, by launching a European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do a lot more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, global wild species populations have declined by approximately 60% since 1970.
The United Nations Conference on Biodiversity, which will be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen the EU's legislation on species protection and put forward a bold plan for a blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to support this green transition.
But we won't be able to accomplish these massive tasks if it's still the same – and most vulnerable – people who are asked to bear the costs.
All measures envisioned will therefore have to be designed first and foremost to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must start working with our partners today for international cooperation, fighting unfair competition.
Because it serves no purpose to have strict European rules on pesticides or forestry management if our imported foods and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three projects could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
Because we are in a state of acute ecological debt, it would be more than justified for the stability and growth pact that applies to the public finances of member states to have an equivalent for green Europe targets.
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action across all sectors: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not be afraid to use its regulatory powers, for instance: expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and "extended producer responsibility" for products on the market could significantly stimulate innovation in favor of the environment.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional €180 billion in investments every year to meet the commitments made under the Paris Agreement.
This is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral climate-focused financier.
And the EU's new budget and investment plan, leveraging private sector investments, could further enhance the Union's power of action.
The financial sector will play a crucial role: through the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as Norway's sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon".
Although some member states will see this as a risky project, we must hold a debate on taxation, but also on subsidies for fossil fuels. In short, on integrating sustainability into public spending.
To support the green transition, we must define ambitious objectives and "missions" with both short- and long-term resonance that genuinely engage society.
With member states and the European Parliament, we will have to determine a common roadmap and engage in in-depth discussions, just as we will with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
This cannot be achieved overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to escape the harsh reality of our environment.
It's already very late to launch a European "Green New Deal". But it's not too late.
Don't let this new opportunity slip away.
